# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: george-hall-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:george-hall-baseball/1871-in-baseball] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1872-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1872 throughout the world.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1873-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1873 throughout the world.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1874-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1876-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1876 throughout the world.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1876-in-baseball] After a tumultuous five-year existence, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) folded following the 1875 season.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1876-in-baseball] One of the new rules put into place by the new league was that all teams had to be located in cities that had a population of 75,000 or more.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1876-in-baseball] The initial NL season began with eight teams, and they were asked to play seventy games between April 22 and October 21.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1876-in-baseball] The NL is often considered to be the first "major league", although it has been argued that the NA can make that claim.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1877 throughout the world.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The **1877 Louisville Grays scandal** was an incident in which members of the Louisville Grays baseball team accepted money to lose games.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Four players – Bill Craver, Jim Devlin, George Hall and Al Nichols – were subsequently banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In the early days of professional baseball, crooked play was not uncommon, and many players were suspected of throwing games in exchange for money.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Illegal influence by gamblers had undermined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) in the early 1870s, and William Hulbert formed the National League (NL) in 1876 with the intention of driving it out of the game.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nevertheless, there were still several gambling-related scandals during the 1876 season.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Jim Devlin started his baseball career in 1873 and was the Louisville Grays' pitcher in 1876 and 1877.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1876 he had a win–loss record of 30–35 and an earned run average of 1.56, while leading the league in complete games, innings pitched and strikeouts.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, Devlin went 35–25 with a 2.25 ERA and again led the league in complete games and innings pitched.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started and completed each of the Grays' 61 games, an accomplishment no other pitcher in history has matched.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Outfielder George Hall was one of the best sluggers in the game's early history.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After playing in the NA from 1871 to 1875, he joined the Philadelphia Athletics in 1876.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] That season, he led the league with five home runs and finished second in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage and total bases.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, he played for the Grays and had a .323 batting average.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Shortstop Bill Craver was a noted crooked player who had been expelled from a previous team for throwing games in 1870.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He played for the New York Mutuals in 1876 before joining the Grays the following season.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Al Nichols also played for the Mutuals in 1876.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He joined the Grays in the middle of the 1877 season on the recommendation of Hall and appeared in six games for the team.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Newspapers named the players "Terror" Devlin, "Gentleman George" Hall, "Butcher" Craver and "Slippery Elm" Nichols".
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After the games of August 13, 1877, the Grays were in first place by four games over St.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louis and 4.5 over the Boston Red Caps, with a record of 27 wins and 13 losses, and with some 20 games left to play.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They then commenced a nine-game winless streak (including one tie) and eventually lost the championship to Boston.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They won six out of their last seven, making their season record of 35-25 look reasonably respectable, but those wins came after Boston had clinched the pennant, having won 20 of their final 21 games.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louisville finished second, seven games behind Boston.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Chase received telegrams informing him of suspicious gambling activity involving the team.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started an investigation, and Devlin and Hall confessed to throwing several exhibition games late in the season, with Devlin receiving up to $100 per game.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 4, the entire team was gathered, and Chase demanded that they turn over their telegrams.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Every player except Craver complied, and the telegrams showed that Devlin, Hall and Nichols had thrown games.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 30, Craver, Devlin, Hall and Nichols were expelled from the club, and on December 4, the NL banned them from professional baseball for the rest of their lives.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The Grays franchise folded after the 1877 season.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Over the next few decades, there were fewer suspicions of game-fixing in professional baseball.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The four banned players were never reinstated.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nichols played semi-professional baseball, Craver and Devlin became police officers, and Hall worked as an engraver and clerk.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Devlin tried to be reinstated many times but was unsuccessful.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In one instance, he got on his knees and begged Hulbert for another chance.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Hulbert responded by handing him $50 (roughly equivalent to $1,200 in 2017 value) and saying, "Devlin, that's what I think of you personally; but, damn you, you have sold a game; you are dishonest and this National League will not stand for it." Devlin died of tuberculosis in 1883.
[src:george-hall-baseball/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] His 1.90 career ERA is the third-lowest of all-time among pitchers with at least 1,000 innings pitched.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] Prior to the inception of professional leagues, Hall played for the Brooklyn Atlantics.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] He commenced his professional career with the Washington Olympics of the National Association in 1871, hitting .294 in 32 games.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] He played for the Baltimore Canaries in 1872 and 1873 seasons, hitting .336 and .345 respectively.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] Playing mostly center field up to this point, he shifted from center to right field the following year when he played for the 1874 champions, the Boston Red Stockings.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] After just one season with the Red Stockings, he moved on to play for the Philadelphia Athletics, where he had another good season at the plate, hitting .299, with four home runs, which placed second in the league behind Jim O'Rourke's six.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] After the 1875 season, the National Association folded, which left room for a new league to begin.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] In 1876, the National League came into existence, the first official "Major League".
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] Hall's team, the Athletics, followed that movement with very little success, finishing seventh out of eight teams.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] One of the bright spots that year for the Athletics was the hitting prowess of their star hitter, Hall.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] He led the team in almost all major hitting categories including a .366 batting average, 51 runs scored, and a league leading five home runs.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] On June 17, 1876, he became the first Major League baseball player to hit two home runs in one game.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] Those five home runs stood as the single season home run record until Charley Jones hit nine in 1879.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] For the 1877 baseball season, Philadelphia had been expelled from the league for refusing to go on a western road trip, late in the 1876 season, for financial reasons, so Hall moved on to play for the Louisville Grays.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] Again, he had an excellent season, hitting .323, scoring 51 runs, and hitting 8 triples.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] Surprisingly, after appearing in the league leaders for home runs the last two seasons, he did not hit one in 1877.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] Some baseball researchers attribute Hall as being the first major league player to hit for the cycle.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] In a game against the Cincinnati Red Stockings on June 14, 1876, Hall had five hits.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] Contemporary newspaper accounts agree that four of the hits were a home run, a single, and two triples; there is disagreement as to if the remaining hit was a double (which would complete the cycle) or another triple.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] The first undisputed major league cycle is attributed to Curry Foley of the Buffalo Bisons of the National League in 1882.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] On October 26, 1877, Louisville club vice president Charles Chase confronted Hall and fellow Gray Jim Devlin with charges that they threw some road games in August and September.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] Both admitted only to throwing non-league games, one of which was an exhibition game in Lowell, Massachusetts, on August 30, and another in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, on September 3.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] The admissions also implicated teammates Al Nichols and Bill Craver.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] Newspapers nicknamed Hall "Gentleman George".
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] Hall claimed that he and Devlin helped in losses to the Cincinnati Reds on September 6 and to the minor league Indianapolis Blues on September 24‚ but he argued that since the Reds were about to be suspended and the games nullified‚ it amounted to an exhibition game.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] As a result of the scandal, all four players were banned for life from Major League Baseball.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] Hall died in Ridgewood, New York, at the age of 74.
[src:george-hall-baseball/george-hall-baseball] He was buried at Evergreen Cemetery in Brooklyn, New York.
